<div>\r\n\r\nCommodity index investments may provide a levered response to inflation.  In other words, one dollar of commodities may hedge more than one dollar of the portfolio from inflation. This concept is called inflation beta. Historically from 1992-2012 for every 1% increase in CPI, the S&amp;P GSCI has had a 16.0% increase and the DJ-UBS CI has had a 10.2% increase. (It is like stock beta, where if stock XXX increased 2% if for every 1% increase S&amp;P 500, then the beta would be 2.)\r\n\r\nClick here to see a table <a href=\"https://dev.indexologyblog.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/06/Inflation-Beta.pptx\" target=\"_blank\">Inflation Beta</a>\r\n\r\nLast, please click here to watch a special video on commodities and inflation from our Index Matters Series with Bob Greer of PIMCO and Boris Shrayer from Morgan Stanley. <a href=\"http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=AcichV7QrWY\" target=\"_blank\">http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=AcichV7QrWY</a>\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n</div>','',557,'https://dev.indexologyblog.com/2013/06/19/557-revision-3/',0,'revision','',0);
