% and  3.5%, respectively today, and each are now bear markets for 2013.  The S&amp;P GSCI Gold, which recorded its biggest daily loss ever on April 15, 2013 of -9.3%, has not had two single day losses of this magnitude in the same year since 1980.\r\n\r\n[caption id=\"attachment_650\" align=\"alignnone\" width=\"269\"]<a href=\"https://dev.indexologyblog.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/06/Biggest-Daily-SP-GSCI-Gold-Losses.jpg\"><img class=\"size-full wp-image-650\" alt=\"Source: S&amp;P Dow Jones Indices. Daily data from 1/06/78 - 6/20/13. Charts and graphs are provided for illustrative purposes only.  Indices are unmanaged statistical composites and their returns do not include payment of any sales charges or fees an investor would pay to purchase the securities the index represents.  Such costs would lower performance.  It is not possible to invest directly in an index.  Past performance is not an indication of future results. The inception date for the S&amp;P GSCI was May 1, 1991, at the market close.  All information presented prior to the index inception date is back-tested. There are inherent limitations associated with back-tested performance. \" src=\"https://dev.indexologyblog.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/06/Biggest-Daily-SP-GSCI-Gold-Losses.jpg\" width=\"269\" height=\"221\" /></a> Source: S&amp;P Dow Jones Indices. Daily data from 1/06/78 - 6/20/13. Charts and graphs are provided for illustrative purposes only. Indices are unmanaged statistical composites and their returns do not include payment of any sales charges or fees an investor would pay to purchase the securities the index represe','',638,'https://dev.indexologyblog.com/2013/06/21/638-revision-13/',0,'revision','',0);
