art reflects hypothetical historical performance.  Please see the Performance Disclosure at the end of this document for more information regarding the inherent limitations associated with backtested performance.\" src=\"https://dev.indexologyblog.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/07/SPGSCI-All-Cattle-2002-13.jpg\" width=\"400\" height=\"166\" /></a> Source: S&amp;P Dow Jones Indices. Data from Jan 2013 to July 17, 2013. Past performance is not an indication of future results. This chart reflects hypothetical historical performance. Please see the Performance Disclosure at the end of this document for more information regarding the inherent limitations associated with backtested performance.[/caption]\r\n\r\nAn obvious driver is that the grilling season has kicked in, but that is on the demand side. Also on the demand side, as reported in the <a href=\"http://www.usda.gov/oce/commodity/wasde/\">United States Department of Agriculture</a> (USDA) report on July 11 was U.S. beef exports rose 4.3% in May from a year ago for muscle meats and 2.7% for total beef and beef variety meat sales. The increase was from a 74% increase in sales to Japan, which eased its age requirement on U.S. beef to cattle under 30 months of age from 20 months or younger.\r\n\r\nIn addition to the rising demand, the summer heat has disrupted supply since cattle eat less when it\'s hotter outside. Also the drought conditions have affected rangelands, leaving little water and forage for livestock, prompting the <a href=\"http://www.blm.gov/wo/st/en.html\">Bureau of Land Management</a> (BLM) to undertake targeted actions, such as reducing grazing.\r\n\r\nLast year beginning in May, the <a href=\"http://us.spindices.com/indices/commodities/sp-gsci-all-cattle\">S&amp;P GSCI All Cattle</a> had a 4 month winning streak driving the index up 7.9% before a small dip in Sep of 1.1%. By the year\'s end the index gained 13.3% from the trough in Apr. Could the drought in 2013 drive similar shortages and higher returns as from the 2012 drought? <a href=\"http://www.4029tv.com/weather/drought-comparison-2012-to-2013/-/8899072/20946326/-/5cgu62/-/index.html\">Compare droughts here</a>.','',919,'https://dev.indexologyblog.com/2013/07/18/919-revision-3/',0,'revision','',0);
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` (`ID`,`post_author`,`post_date`,`post_date_gmt`,`post_title`,`post_excerpt`,`post_status`,`comment_status`,`ping_status`,`post_password`,`post_name`,`to_ping`,`pinged`,`post_modified`,`post_modified_gmt`,`post_content`,`post_content_filtered`,`post_parent`,`guid`,`menu_order`,`post_type`,`post_mime_type`,`comment_count`) VALUES (925,7,'2013-07-19 13:28:08','2013-07-19 13:28:08','When Diversification Fails','','publish','open','open','','when-diversification-fails','','','2013-08-05 14:25:30','2013-08-05 14:25:30','Diversification means different things in different contexts.  We can speak, for example, of diversification within an equity portfolio -- i.e., of holding a number of stocks with potentially-offsetting risks, as opposed to concentrating on only one issue or on a handful of similar stocks.  Or we can think of diversification across asset classes -- e.g., by adding bonds, or international stocks, or commodities to a (diversified) U.S. equity portfolio.  Conventional wisdom smiles on these two forms of diversification, and rightly so, since the final diversified portfolio typically has a higher expected return, or lower expected risk, than the starting portfolio.\r\n\r\nBut diversification might not always be a good idea.  Suppose I go a casino, find the roulette wheel, and bet on a number at random.  I’m likely to lose my money.  If I do the same thing a second time, and a third, the result is likely to be the same.  <strong>I haven\'t created a diversified portfolio of bets -- I\'ve merely repeated the same mistake several times over.</strong>\r\n\r\nA recent <a href=\"http://www.rickferri.com/WhitePaper.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">white paper</a> asks whether the selection of active investment managers is a useful or fruitless form of diversification.  (Spoiler alert: fruitless.)  Why?  Active managers, more often than not, <a href=\"http://us.spindices.com/documents/spiva/spiva-us-year-end-2012.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">underperform</a> the indices against which they’re benchmarked.  An investor who chooses an actively-managed fund over an index fund is therefore more likely than not to underperform.  Adding a second and third actively-managed fund is likely to leave the investor worse off than he was with only one (just as multiple turns at the roulette wheel are likely to leave a gambler poorer than he was after his first bet).\r\n\r\n<strong>If it were easy to find outperforming active funds, diversifying active management might be beneficial.</strong>  But it\'s not easy -- and that implies, as discussed <a href=\"http://www.spindices.com/multimedia-center/portfolio-structure-index-vs-active\" target=\"_blank\">here</a>, that picking active managers is one of those areas where diversification fails.','',0,'https://dev.indexologyblog.com/?p=925',0,'post','',1);
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` (`ID`,`post_author`,`post_date`,`post_date_gmt`,`post_title`,`post_excerpt`,`post_status`,`comment_status`,`ping_status`,`post_password`,`post_name`,`to_ping`,`pinged`,`post_modified`,`post_modified_gmt`,`post_content`,`post_content_filtered`,`post_parent`,`guid`,`menu_order`,`post_type`,`post_mime_type`,`comment_count`) VALUES (926,7,'2013-07-18 21:07:34','2013-07-18 21:07:34','When Diversification Fails','','inherit','open','open','','925-revision','','','2013-07-18 21:07:34','2013-07-18 21:07:34','Diversification means different things in different contexts.  We can speak, for example, of diversification within an equity portfolio—i.e., of holding a number of stocks with potentially-offsetting risks, as opposed to concentrating on only one issue or on a handful of similar stocks.  Or we can think of diversification across asset classes—e.g., by adding bonds, or international stocks, or commodities to a (diversified) U.S. equity portfolio.  Conventional wisdom smiles on these two forms of diversification, and rightly so.\n\nBut diversification might not always be a good idea.  Suppose I go to the race track, choose a horse at random, and make a bet.  I’m likely to lose my money.  If I do the same thing in the second race, and the third, the result is likely to be the same.  A diversified portfolio of bets can leave me worse off than my original undiversified bet.  Diversification is beneficial only if the final diversified portfolio has a higher expected return, or lower expected risk, than the starting portfolio.  That’s why investors typically diversify both within and across asset classes.\n\nA recent <a href=\"http://www.rickferri.com/WhitePaper.pdf\">white paper</a> asks whether the selection of active investment managers is a useful or fruitless form of diversification.  (Spoiler alert: fruitless.)  Why?  Because active managers, more often than not, <a href=\"http://us.spindices.com/documents/spiva/spiva-us-year-end-2012.pdf\">underperform</a> the indices against which they’re benchmarked.  An investor who chooses an actively-managed fund over an index therefore is more likely than not to underperform.  Adding a second and third actively-managed fund is likely to leave the investor worse off than he was with only one active fund.','',925,'https://dev.indexologyblog.com/2013/07/18/925-revision/',0,'revision','',0);
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` (`ID`,`post_author`,`post_date`,`post_date_gmt`,`post_title`,`post_excerpt`,`post_status`,`comment_status`,`ping_status`,`post_password`,`post_name`,`to_ping`,`pinged`,`post_modified`,`post_modified_gmt`,`post_content`,`post_content_filtered`,`post_parent`,`guid`,`menu_order`,`post_type`,`post_mime_type`,`comment_count`) VALUES (927,7,'2013-07-18 22:25:27','2013-07-18 22:25:27','When Diversification Fails','','inherit','open','open','','925-revision-2','','','2013-07-18 22:25:27','2013-07-18 22:25:27','Diversification means different things in different contexts.  We can speak, for example, of diversification within an equity portfolio—i.e., of holding a number of stocks with potentially-offsetting risks, as opposed to concentrating on only one issue or on a handful of similar stocks.  Or we can think of diversification across asset classes—e.g., by adding bonds, or international stocks, or commodities to a (diversified) U.S. equity portfolio.  Conventional wisdom smiles on these two forms of diversification, and rightly so.\n\nBut diversification might not always be a good idea.  Suppose I go to the race track, choose a horse at random, and make a bet.  I’m likely to lose my money.  If I do the same thing in the second race, and the third, the result is likely to be the same.  A diversified portfolio of bets can leave me worse off than my original undiversified bet.  Diversification is beneficial only if the final diversified portfolio has a higher expected return, or lower expected risk, than the starting portfolio.  That’s why investors typically diversify both within and across asset classes.\n\nA recent <a href=\"http://www.rickferri.com/WhitePaper.pdf\">white paper</a> asks whether the selection of active investment managers is a useful or fruitless form of diversification.  (Spoiler alert: fruitless.)  Why?  Because active managers, more often than not, <a href=\"http://us.spindices.com/documents/spiva/spiva-us-year-end-2012.pdf\">underperform</a> the indices against which they’re benchmarked.  An investor who chooses an actively-managed fund over an index therefore is more likely than not to underperform.  Adding a second and third actively-managed fund is likely to leave the investor worse off than he was with the original active fund.\n\nIf it were easy to find outperforming active funds, diversification might be beneficial. But it\'s not easy -- and that implies, as discussed here, that picking active managers is one of those areas where diversification fails','',925,'https://dev.indexologyblog.com/2013/07/18/925-revision-2/',0,'revision','',0);
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` (`ID`,`post_author`,`post_date`,`post_date_gmt`,`post_title`,`post_excerpt`,`post_status`,`comment_status`,`ping_status`,`post_password`,`post_name`,`to_ping`,`pinged`,`post_modified`,`post_modified_gmt`,`post_content`,`post_content_filtered`,`post_parent`,`guid`,`menu_order`,`post_type`,`post_mime_type`,`comment_count`) VALUES (928,7,'2013-07-18 22:27:36','2013-07-18 22:27:36','When Diversification Fails','','inherit','open','open','','925-revision-3','','','2013-07-18 22:27:36','2013-07-18 22:27:36','Diversification means different things in different contexts.  We can speak, for example, of diversification within an equity portfolio—i.e., of holding a number of stocks with potentially-offsetting risks, as opposed to concentrating on only one issue or on a handful of similar stocks.  Or we can think of diversification across asset classes—e.g., by adding bonds, or international stocks, or commodities to a (diversified) U.S. equity portfolio.  Conventional wisdom smiles on these two forms of diversification, and rightly so.\n\nBut diversification might not always be a good idea.  Suppose I go to the race track, choose a horse at random, and make a bet.  I’m likely to lose my money.  If I do the same thing in the second race, and the third, the result is likely to be the same.  A diversified portfolio of bets can leave me worse off than my original undiversified bet.  Diversification is beneficial only if the final diversified portfolio has a higher expected return, or lower expected risk, than the starting portfolio.  That’s why investors typically diversify both within and across asset classes.\n\nA recent <a href=\"http://www.rickferri.com/WhitePaper.pdf\">white paper</a> asks whether the selection of active investment managers is a useful or fruitless form of diversification.  (Spoiler alert: fruitless.)  Why?  Because active managers, more often than not, <a href=\"http://us.spindices.com/documents/spiva/spiva-us-year-end-2012.pdf\">underperform</a> the indices against which they’re benchmarked.  An investor who chooses an actively-managed fund over an index therefore is more likely than not to underperform.  Adding a second and third actively-managed fund is likely to leave the investor worse off than he was with only one.\n\nIf it were easy to find outperforming active funds, diversification might be beneficial. But it\'s not easy -- and that implies, as discussed here, that picking active managers is one of those areas where diversification fails','',925,'https://dev.indexologyblog.com/2013/07/18/925-revision-3/',0,'revision','',0);
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` (`ID`,`post_author`,`post_date`,`post_date_gmt`,`post_title`,`post_excerpt`,`post_status`,`comment_status`,`ping_status`,`post_password`,`post_name`,`to_ping`,`pinged`,`post_modified`,`post_modified_gmt`,`post_content`,`post_content_filtered`,`post_parent`,`guid`,`menu_order`,`post_type`,`post_mime_type`,`comment_count`) VALUES (929,7,'2013-07-19 12:34:50','2013-07-19 12:34:50','When Diversification Fails','','inherit','open','open','','925-revision-4','','','2013-07-19 12:34:50','2013-07-19 12:34:50','Diversification means different things in different contexts.  We can speak, for example, of diversification within an equity portfolio -- i.e., of holding a number of stocks with potentially-offsetting risks, as opposed to concentrating on only one issue or on a handful of similar stocks.  Or we can think of diversification across asset classes -- e.g., by adding bonds, or international stocks, or commodities to a (diversified) U.S. equity portfolio.  Conventional wisdom smiles on these two forms of diversification, and rightly so, since the final diversified portfolio typically has a higher expected return, or lower expected risk, than the starting portfolio.\n\nBut diversification might not always be a good idea.  Suppose I go a casino, find the roulette wheel, and bet on a number at random.  I’m likely to lose my money.  If I do the same thing a second time, and a third, the result is likely to be the same.  <strong>I haven\'t created a diversified portfolio of bets -- I\'ve merely repeated the same mistake several times over.</strong>\n\nA recent <a href=\"http://www.rickferri.com/WhitePaper.pdf\">white paper</a> asks whether the selection of active investment managers is a useful or fruitless form of diversification.  (Spoiler alert: fruitless.)  Why?  Active managers, more often than not, <a href=\"http://us.spindices.com/documents/spiva/spiva-us-year-end-2012.pdf\">underperform</a> the indices against which they’re benchmarked.  An investor who chooses an actively-managed fund over an index fund is therefore more likely than not to underperform.  Adding a second and third actively-managed fund is likely to leave the investor worse off than he was with only one (just as multiple bets at the roulette wheel are likely to leave a gambler poorer than he was after his first bet).\n\n<strong>If it were easy to find outperforming active funds, diversifying active management might be beneficial.</strong>  But it\'s not easy -- and that implies, as discussed <a href=\"http://www.spindices.com/multimedia-center/portfolio-structure-index-vs-active\">here</a>, that picking active managers is one of those areas where diversification fails.','',925,'https://dev.indexologyblog.com/2013/07/19/925-revision-4/',0,'revision','',0);
