ef=\"http://us.spindices.com/search/?query=modified+weight&amp;Search=SEARCH&amp;Search=SEARCH\" target=\"_blank\">weights</a> may have seemed to be the smarter solution since backwardation was a thing of the past. However, today that wisdom may not hold true because w</span>hile the <a title=\"Keeping Up With Contango’s Twist\" href=\"https://dev.indexologyblog.com/2013/07/08/keeping-up-with-contangos-twist/\">persistence of backwardation</a> hasn\'t been seen since prior to 2005, backwardation (as measured by the difference between the excess return and price return versions of the  <a href=\"http://us.spindices.com/index-family/commodities/sp-gsci\" target=\"_blank\">S&amp;P GSCI</a>), appeared in 5 months in 2012 an has now continued since May 2013.\r\n\r\nThere is a noticeable shift of world growth that may be causing backwardation to reappear. A number of <a href=\"http://www.zerohedge.com/article/coming-new-world-order-revolution-how-things-will-change-next-20-years-kondratieff-cycle-per\" target=\"_blank\">characteristics of world growth</a> driven by expansion of demand are becoming more widespread by the move from world growth driven by expansion of supply.  These factors are getting stronger since last year and they may drive the frequency and magnitude of cycles higher that may increase the frequency of switching between contango and backwardation.\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://www.zerohedge.com/sites/default/files/images/user5/imageroot/draghi/NWO%201.jpg\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-1045\" alt=\"New World\" src=\"https://dev.indexologyblog.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/New-World.jpg\" width=\"1065\" height=\"513\" /','',1038,'https://dev.indexologyblog.com/2013/08/06/1038-revision-18/',0,'revision','',0);
