ds roughly doubled the value of the investment.  Looking at the same time period, the annual return earned by the total return index was 9.71% and by the price index was 6.96%, a spread of 2.75%.\r\n\r\n <a href=\"https://dev.indexologyblog.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/500TR.jpg\"><img class=\"alignnone size-large wp-image-1134\" alt=\"500TR\" src=\"https://dev.indexologyblog.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/500TR-1024x791.jpg\" width=\"625\" height=\"482\" /></a>','',1123,'https://dev.indexologyblog.com/2013/08/08/1123-revision-8/',0,'revision','',0);
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` (`ID`,`post_author`,`post_date`,`post_date_gmt`,`post_title`,`post_excerpt`,`post_status`,`comment_status`,`ping_status`,`post_password`,`post_name`,`to_ping`,`pinged`,`post_modified`,`post_modified_gmt`,`post_content`,`post_content_filtered`,`post_parent`,`guid`,`menu_order`,`post_type`,`post_mime_type`,`comment_count`) VALUES (1138,5,'2013-08-08 21:28:36','2013-08-08 21:28:36','The Good Calls and Bad Calls of Covered Calls ','','inherit','open','open','','1120-revision','','','2013-08-08 21:28:36','2013-08-08 21:28:36','Generally investors use covered calls to earn extra income from investments they think might not have much upside potential.  For example, if a CEO has a very large stock holding in his or her company but doubts the stock price will increase (or decrease much), writing (selling) options on the stock to collect a premium may be a good solution to earn some extra income.\n\nIn the past few years, one of the index innovations has expanded on this concept for commodities in the <a href=\"http://www.spindices.com/indices/commodities/sp-gsci-covered-call-select\">S&amp;P GSCI Covered Call Select</a>. The index is an equally weighted composite of 10 single covered call commodity indices based on the liquidity in the options market, where the annual options volume must be at least 10% of the underlying commodity futures volume. The index intends to produce income and reduce volatility as well as negative roll yield from <a title=\"Keeping Up With Contango’s Twist\" href=\"https://dev.indexologyblog.com/2013/07/08/keeping-up-with-contangos-twist/\" target=\"_blank\">contango</a>.\n\nThe commodities included in the index currently are: coffee, corn, <a title=\"A Pot of Cotton at the End of the Rainbow Year-to-Date S&amp;P GSCI is off 0.19%\" href=\"https://dev.indexologyblog.com/2013/03/15/a-pot-of-cotton-at-the-end-of-the-rainbow-year-to-date-sp-gsci-is-off-0-19/\" target=\"_blank\">cotton</a>, <a title=\"Paying Too Much at the Pump?!\" href=\"https://dev.indexologyblog.com/2013/08/01/paying-too-much-at-the-pump/\" target=\"_blank\">WTI crude oil</a>, <a title=\"THE Golden Question?\" href=\"https://dev.indexologyblog.com/2013/07/25/the-golden-question/\" target=\"_blank\">gold</a>, natural gas, <a title=\"S&amp;P GSCI Precious Metals Hits Lowest Since October 2010\" href=\"https://dev.indexologyblog.com/2013/06/18/sp-gsci-precious-metals-hits-lowest-since-october-2010/\" target=\"_blank\">silver</a>, soybeans, sugar, and wheat. So, which covered calls were good calls and which were bad calls and how does it change in different times?\n\n&nbsp;','',1120,'https://dev.indexologyblog.com/2013/08/08/1120-revision/',0,'revision','',0);
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` (`ID`,`post_author`,`post_date`,`post_date_gmt`,`post_title`,`post_excerpt`,`post_status`,`comment_status`,`ping_status`,`post_password`,`post_name`,`to_ping`,`pinged`,`post_modified`,`post_modified_gmt`,`post_content`,`post_content_filtered`,`post_parent`,`guid`,`menu_order`,`post_type`,`post_mime_type`,`comment_count`) VALUES (1140,5,'2013-08-08 21:50:01','2013-08-08 21:50:01','Covered Call','Source: S&amp;P Dow Jones Indices.  Data from Mar 2003 to July  2013.  Past performance is not an indication of future results.  This chart reflects hypothetical historical performance.  Please see the Performance Disclosure at the end of this document for more information regarding the inherent limitations associated with backtested performance.','inherit','open','open','','covered-call','','','2013-08-08 21:50:01','2013-08-08 21:50:01','','',1120,'https://dev.indexologyblog.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/Covered-Call.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0);
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` (`ID`,`post_author`,`post_date`,`post_date_gmt`,`post_title`,`post_excerpt`,`post_status`,`comment_status`,`ping_status`,`post_password`,`post_name`,`to_ping`,`pinged`,`post_modified`,`post_modified_gmt`,`post_content`,`post_content_filtered`,`post_parent`,`guid`,`menu_order`,`post_type`,`post_mime_type`,`comment_count`) VALUES (1141,5,'2013-08-08 21:55:12','2013-08-08 21:55:12','The Good Calls and Bad Calls of Covered Calls ','','inherit','open','open','','1120-revision-2','','','2013-08-08 21:55:12','2013-08-08 21:55:12','Generally investors use covered calls to earn extra income from investments they think might not have much upside potential.  For example, if a CEO has a very large stock holding in his or her company but doubts the stock price will increase (or decrease much), writing (selling) options on the stock to collect a premium may be a good solution to earn some extra income.\n\nIn the past few years, one of the index innovations has expanded on this concept for commodities in the <a href=\"http://www.spindices.com/indices/commodities/sp-gsci-covered-call-select\">S&amp;P GSCI Covered Call Select</a>. The index is an equally weighted composite of 10 single covered call commodity indices based on the liquidity in the options market, where the annual options volume must be at least 10% of the underlying commodity futures volume. The index intends to produce income and reduce volatility as well as negative roll yield from <a title=\"Keeping Up With Contango’s Twist\" href=\"https://dev.indexologyblog.com/2013/07/08/keeping-up-with-contangos-twist/\" target=\"_blank\">contango</a>.\n\nThe commodities included in the index currently are: coffee, corn, <a title=\"A Pot of Cotton at the End of the Rainbow Year-to-Date S&amp;P GSCI is off 0.19%\" href=\"https://dev.indexologyblog.com/2013/03/15/a-pot-of-cotton-at-the-end-of-the-rainbow-year-to-date-sp-gsci-is-off-0-19/\" target=\"_blank\">cotton</a>, <a title=\"Paying Too Much at the Pump?!\" href=\"https://dev.indexologyblog.com/2013/08/01/paying-too-much-at-the-pump/\" target=\"_blank\">WTI crude oil</a>, <a title=\"THE Golden Question?\" href=\"https://dev.indexologyblog.com/2013/07/25/the-golden-question/\" target=\"_blank\">gold</a>, natural gas, <a title=\"S&amp;P GSCI Precious Metals Hits Lowest Since October 2010\" href=\"https://dev.indexologyblog.com/2013/06/18/sp-gsci-precious-metals-hits-lowest-since-october-2010/\" target=\"_blank\">silver</a>, soybeans, sugar, and wheat. So, which covered calls were good calls and which were bad calls and how does it change in <a title=\"Index Rehab: Is Backwardation Back In-Style?\" href=\"https://dev.indexologyblog.com/2013/08/06/index-rehab-is-backwardation-back-in-style/\">different times</a>? Overall, the option risk premium for the <a href=\"http://www.spindices.com/indices/commodities/sp-gsci-covered-call-select\">S&amp;P GSCI Covered Call Select</a> in the time frame from Mar 2003 - Jul 2013 (the period we have data for) was 8.1%.  See the chart below for the monthly premium. 63% or 79/125 of the months were positive.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n[caption id=\"attachment_1140\" align=\"alignnone\" width=\"637\"]<img class=\"size-full wp-image-1140\" alt=\"Source: S&amp;P Dow Jones Indices.  Data from Mar 2003 to July  2013.  Past performance is not an indication of future results.  This chart reflects hypothetical historical performance.  Please see the Performance Disclosure at the end of this document for more information regarding the inherent limitations associated with backtested performance.\" src=\"https://dev.indexologyblog.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/Covered-Call.jpg\" width=\"637\" height=\"419\" /> Source: S&amp;P Dow Jones Indices. Data from Mar 2003 to July 2013. Past performance is not an indication of future results. This chart reflects hypothetical historical performance. Please see the Performance Disclosure at the end of this document for more information regarding the inherent limitations associated with backtested performance.[/caption]\n\n&nbsp;','',1120,'https://dev.indexologyblog.com/2013/08/08/1120-revision-2/',0,'revision','',0);
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` (`ID`,`post_author`,`post_date`,`post_date_gmt`,`post_title`,`post_excerpt`,`post_status`,`comment_status`,`ping_status`,`post_password`,`post_name`,`to_ping`,`pinged`,`post_modified`,`post_modified_gmt`,`post_content`,`post_content_filtered`,`post_parent`,`guid`,`menu_order`,`post_type`,`post_mime_type`,`comment_count`) VALUES (1142,5,'2013-08-08 22:19:09','2013-08-08 22:19:09','Good Calls and Bad Calls of Covered Calls ','','inherit','open','open','','1120-revision-3','','','2013-08-08 22:19:09','2013-08-08 22:19:09','Generally investors use covered calls to earn extra income from investments they think might not have much upside potential.  For example, if a CEO has a very large stock holding in his or her company but doubts the stock price will increase (or decrease much), writing (selling) options on the stock to collect a premium may be a good solution to earn some extra income.\n\nIn the past few years, one of the index innovations has expanded on this concept for commodities in the <a href=\"http://www.spindices.com/indices/commodities/sp-gsci-covered-call-select\">S&amp;P GSCI Covered Call Select</a>. The index is an equally weighted composite of 10 single covered call commodity indices based on the liquidity in the options market, where the annual options volume must be at least 10% of the underlying commodity futures volume. The index intends to produce income and reduce volatility as well as negative roll yield from <a title=\"Keeping Up With Contango’s Twist\" href=\"https://dev.indexologyblog.com/2013/07/08/keeping-up-with-contangos-twist/\" target=\"_blank\">contango</a>.\n\nThe commodities included in the index currently are: coffee, corn, <a title=\"A Pot of Cotton at the End of the Rainbow Year-to-Date S&amp;P GSCI is off 0.19%\" href=\"https://dev.indexologyblog.com/2013/03/15/a-pot-of-cotton-at-the-end-of-the-rainbow-year-to-date-sp-gsci-is-off-0-19/\" target=\"_blank\">cotton</a>, <a title=\"Paying Too Much at the Pump?!\" href=\"https://dev.indexologyblog.com/2013/08/01/paying-too-much-at-the-pump/\" target=\"_blank\">WTI crude oil</a>, <a title=\"THE Golden Question?\" href=\"https://dev.indexologyblog.com/2013/07/25/the-golden-question/\" target=\"_blank\">gold</a>, natural gas, <a title=\"S&amp;P GSCI Precious Metals Hits Lowest Since October 2010\" href=\"https://dev.indexologyblog.com/2013/06/18/sp-gsci-precious-metals-hits-lowest-since-october-2010/\" target=\"_blank\">silver</a>, soybeans, sugar, and wheat. So, which covered calls were good calls and which were bad calls and how does it change in <a title=\"Index Rehab: Is Backwardation Back In-Style?\" href=\"https://dev.indexologyblog.com/2013/08/06/index-rehab-is-backwardation-back-in-style/\">different times</a>? Overall, the option risk premium for the <a href=\"http://www.spindices.com/indices/commodities/sp-gsci-covered-call-select\">S&amp;P GSCI Covered Call Select</a> was 8.1% in the time frame from Mar 2003 - Jul 2013 (the period we have data for).  See the chart below for the monthly premiums. 63% or 79/125 of the months had positive premiums where in 60% of months prior to 2008, 79% of months between 2008-9, and 58% of months post 2009 had positive premiums.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<img class=\"size-full wp-image-1140\" alt=\"Source: S&amp;P Dow Jones Indices.  Data from Mar 2003 to July  2013.  Past performance is not an indication of future results.  This chart reflects hypothetical historical performance.  Please see the Performance Disclosure at the end of this document for more information regarding the inherent limitations associated with backtested performance.\" src=\"https://dev.indexologyblog.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/Covered-Call.jpg\" width=\"637\" height=\"419\" />\n\n<dl class=\"wp-caption alignnone\" id=\"attachment_1140\" style=\"width: 647px\"><dd class=\"wp-caption-dd\">Source: S&amp;P Dow Jones Indices. Data from Mar 2003 to July 2013. Past performance is not an indication of future results. This chart reflects hypothetical historical performance. Please see the Performance Disclosure at the end of this document for more information regarding the inherent limitations associated with backtested performance.</dd></dl>&nbsp;','',1120,'https://dev.indexologyblog.com/2013/08/08/1120-revision-3/',0,'revision','',0);
